---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import Breadcrumbs from '@components/Breadcrumbs.astro';
import { url } from '@lib/url';
---

<BaseLayout title="How We Review" description="Ounce Ledger's methodology, stated plainly: research synthesis of manufacturer specs, verified owner reviews, and published third-party testing — with no fabricated field testing, ever.">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 py-8">
    <Breadcrumbs crumbs={[{ label: 'Home', href: '/' }, { label: 'How We Review' }]} />
    <h1 class="mt-4 text-3xl font-bold tracking-tight">How we review gear</h1>

    <div class="prose mt-6">
      <p>
        <strong>The most important thing on this page: we do not field-test the gear we write about, and
        no article on this site will ever claim we did.</strong> There is no garage full of tents here, no
        gear closet, no staff photographer on the Pacific Crest Trail. Sites that fake that experience are
        the reason you should be skeptical of gear reviews — including ours. So here is exactly what we do
        instead, and why we think it's honest and useful.
      </p>

      <h2>Our method: research synthesis</h2>
      <p>Every recommendation is built from three source types, in this order of trust:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Manufacturer specifications</strong> — weight, dimensions, materials, and ratings taken
          from the manufacturer's own published spec sheet, recorded with a source link in an internal
          research document before the article is written. When a manufacturer doesn't publish a number,
          we print "not published." We never estimate, average, or guess a spec.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Verified owner reviews</strong> — patterns across large numbers of purchase-verified
          reviews on multiple retailers. One review means nothing; two hundred people independently
          reporting a zipper failure means something. We report the pattern, not cherry-picked quotes.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Published third-party testing</strong> — independent lab measurements and long-term
          field reports from publications and testers who do physically use the gear. Where our specs or
          conclusions rely on their work, that's recorded in the research document.
        </li>
      </ol>

      <h2>What our awards mean</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Top pick</strong> — best overall balance of weight, durability evidence, and price band for the target reader (a beginner-to-intermediate multi-day backpacker).</li>
        <li><strong>Budget pick</strong> — the cheapest option we'd actually put in a pack, not the cheapest option that exists.</li>
        <li><strong>Lightweight pick</strong> — the lightest option whose durability evidence doesn't disqualify it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Rules we enforce in code</h2>
      <p>
        These aren't aspirations — an automated integrity check runs on every single build, and the site
        literally cannot publish if a rule is violated:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>No claimed first-hand testing, wearing, carrying, or field use. Phrases that fake experience fail the build.</li>
        <li>Every weight, price, and dimension traces to a source recorded in a research document.</li>
        <li>Unknown specs render as "not published," never a guess.</li>
        <li>No fake urgency, fake scarcity, invented review counts, or fabricated quotes.</li>
        <li>Prices appear as bands ($ / $$ / $$$) so they can't silently go stale.</li>
        <li>An affiliate disclosure appears above the fold on every page with affiliate links.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How money flows (and doesn't)</h2>
      <p>
        The site earns affiliate commissions when you buy through our links — details on the
        <a href={url('/affiliate-disclosure/')}>affiliate disclosure page</a>. What we don't do: accept
        payment for placement, let a commission rate change a ranking, or take free products in exchange
        for coverage. Rankings are set before monetization is considered, and the same registry of links
        is used regardless of which product wins.
      </p>

      <h2>Corrections</h2>
      <p>
        If a spec on this site is wrong, <a href={url('/contact/')}>tell us</a> and cite the source. We'd
        rather correct a number than defend it. Corrections update the article's "updated" date.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
